      <hedline>
        <hl1>Inquiry Sought In Lazio Trades</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>New York State Comptroller H Carl McCall, ally of Hillary Rodham Clinton, calls for an insider trader inquiry into profits earned by her Senate opponent, Representative Rick A Lazio, in connection with stock of Quick &amp; Reilly (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>State Comptroller H. Carl McCall, an ally of Hillary Rodham Clinton, called yesterday for an insider trader inquiry into profits earned by her Senate opponent, Representative Rick A. Lazio.</p>
        <p>Mr. McCall sent a letter to the Securities and Exchange Commission about Mr. Lazio's windfall from trading in stock and options in Quick &amp; Reilly, a brokerage company controlled by Lazio campaign contributors.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>State Comptroller H. Carl McCall, an ally of Hillary Rodham Clinton, called yesterday for an insider trader inquiry into profits earned by her Senate opponent, Representative Rick A. Lazio.</p>
        <p>Mr. McCall sent a letter to the Securities and Exchange Commission about Mr. Lazio's windfall from trading in stock and options in Quick &amp; Reilly, a brokerage company controlled by Lazio campaign contributors.</p>
        <p>Mr. Lazio's aides say he did not have inside information before making the trades, which in one case reaped a profit of about $13,500, or nearly 600 percent, in less than seven weeks. The aides described the McCall request as a political stunt. The Securities and Exchange Commission declined to comment.</p>
      </block>
